<h2 id="Multiplying-a-Number-Mutiple-Times">Multiplying a Number Mutiple Times<a class="anchor-link" href="#Multiplying-a-Number-Mutiple-Times">&#182;</a></h2><p>Before we talk about the Euler number, I would like to conceptually define the powers of a number.</p>
<p>What is the result of multiplying '2' four times? <br></p>
<blockquote><p>$ 2\times2\times2\times2 = 16 $</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Then, do it for three times, two times, one times, and zero times.<br></p>
<blockquote><p><code>3 times:</code> $ 2\times2\times2 = 8 $ <br>
<code>2 times:</code> $ 2\times2 = 4 $ <br>
<code>1 times:</code> $ 2 = 2 $</p>
</blockquote>
<p>How do we define multiplying zero times? It seems reasonable to introduce the identity element of the multiplication.</p>
<blockquote><p><code>3 times:</code> $ 1\times2\times2\times2 = 8 $ <br>
<code>2 times:</code> $ 1\times2\times2 = 4 $ <br>
<code>1 times:</code> $ 1\times2 = 2 $ <br>
<code>0 times:</code> $ 1 = 1 $</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Can we do -1 times or -2 times? From above, I observe from above results that the value becomes 1/2 every time we decrement the number of multiplication.</p>
<blockquote><p><code>+3 times:</code> $ 8 $ <br>
<code>+2 times:</code> $ 8 \div 2 = 4 $ <br>
<code>+1 times:</code> $ 8 \div 2 \div 2 = 2 $ <br>
<code>+0 times:</code> $ 8 \div 2 \div 2 \div 2 = 1 $ <br>
<code>-1 times:</code> $ 8 \div 2 \div 2 \div 2 \div 2 = 1/2 $ <br></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Dividing by 2 works well with the definition of zero-times multiplication.</p>
<p>Now we tasted some flavor of this type of multiplication. In mathematics, we call x-times multiplication of the number n:</p>
<ul>
<li>x'th power of n</li>
<li>n to the power of x</li>
<li>n to the x'th power</li>
<li>or simply $ n^x $</li>
</ul>

<p>This function $ y=n^x $ is called an exponential function. n and x are called base and exponent, respectively.</p>
<p>Let me make more solid definition of the exponent based on our observations as:</p>
<ul>
<li>$n^x$ is multiplied by n whenever x increments by one</li>
<li>Exponent can be any number -not limited to integers-</li>
</ul>
<p>Other properties can be quickly derived as:</p>
<ul>
<li>$n^x \cdot n^{y} = n^{(x+y)}$</li>
<li>$(n\cdot m)^x = n^x\cdot m^x$</li>
<li>$n^0=1$ because $ n^1 \cdot n^0 = n^{(1+0)} $, therefore </li>
<li>$n^{-x}=1 / n^x $ because $ n^{-x} \cdot n^{x} = n^0 = 1 $</li>
<li>$(n^{x})^y=n^{x\cdot y}$ </li>
</ul>
<p>An exponent of fractional numbers can be understood from the following examples.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>$n^{0.1}$ is a number that becomes n when multipled 10 times.</p>
<blockquote><p>because $ (n^{0.1})^{10} = n $</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>$n^{1.1}$ is a number that becomes $n^{11}$ when multipled 10 times.</p>
<blockquote><p>because $ (n^{1.1})^{10} = n^{11} $</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="The-Slope-of-Exponential-Functions">The Slope of Exponential Functions<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Slope-of-Exponential-Functions">&#182;</a></h2><p>The rate of change, or the slope of the curve or the first derivative is really important in math, science and engineering. For fun, let's examine the rate of change for the function $ f:y = 2^x $, which is plotted above.</p>
<p>Let's say that x is changed by +h from x to x+h. Then the y is changed from $f(x)$ to $f(x+h)$. The rate of change is then:</p>
<p>$$ f'(x) = \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{x+h-x} = \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$</p>
<p>In this particular case, it is</p>
<p>$$ \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2^{(x+h)}-2^x}{h} = 2^x \cdot \frac{(2^h-1)}{h} $$</p>
<p>By the way, the slope of the function at x=0 is</p>
<p>$$ f'(0) = \frac{dy}{dx}(0) = \frac{f(0+h)-f(0)}{h} = \frac{(2^h-2^0)}{h} = \frac{(2^h-1)}{h}$$</p>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<p>$$ f'(x) = f'(0) \cdot 2^x $$</p>
<p>It seems that we are stuck but in fact the sloe at x=0 is simply a constant. We just don't know what the value is now. As a quick remedy, let's say $ C = f'(c) $ then,</p>
<p>$$ f'(x) = C \cdot 2^x $$</p>
<p>It looks like the slope of exponential function is actually another exponential function with the same base. This is in fact a very nice property and one of the greeatest findings in human history. Also note that the slope at x=0 depends on the base 'n' as shown below. -the larger the base, the larger the slope-</p>
<div id="figure3"></div>

<h2 id="Finding-'e'">Finding 'e'<a class="anchor-link" href="#Finding-'e'">&#182;</a></h2><p>From above, it is easy to get the derivative of the exponential function with base 'n':</p>
<p>$$f(x) = n^x$$ $$ f'(x) = f'(0) \cdot n^x $$</p>
<p>Now, how do we figure $f'(0)$ out? Is there a certain base number that gives $f'(0)=1$? This would be the key to get the derivative of any exponential function. (it is true. <a href="">future link</a>) We are facing a large wall and this is a good motivation for introducing a new tool to overcome it. Let's give the glorious name of <strong>e</strong> to the number that satisfy the following equation.</p>
<p>$$ f(x) = e^x \\ f'(0) = 1 \\ f'(x)=f(x) $$</p>
<p>Then,</p>
<p>$$ f'(x) = e^x \cdot \frac{(e^h-1)}{h} = e^x $$</p>
<p>After rearranging,</p>
<p>$$ e^h = h+1 $$</p>
<p>$$ (e^h)^{1/h} = (h+1)^{1/h} $$</p>
<p>$$ e = (h+1)^{1/h} $$</p>
<p>Now limiting h -&gt; 0, <strong>e</strong> is very large power of a number that is very close to but larger than 1. Let's see how this number converges by calculating the number with differnt h's from 1 to 0.001.</p>

<h2 id="We-Just-Devised-'e'">We Just Devised 'e'<a class="anchor-link" href="#We-Just-Devised-'e'">&#182;</a></h2><p>This may not be how <strong>e</strong> is defined and invented for the first time in humna history. But I believe that there must be similar occasions where mathmaticians had to define this number to facilitate solving hard problems. This article introduced a number that satisfies a certain condition to solve a hard problem. - though the problem is not solved here yet, I'll right that parts up later - Thanks to that nice property -the satisfied condition-, <strong>e</strong> facilitated tons of problems in the world since its birthday.</p>

<h2 id="Appendix:-Finding-'e'-using-Infinite-Series">Appendix: Finding 'e' using Infinite Series<a class="anchor-link" href="#Appendix:-Finding-'e'-using-Infinite-Series">&#182;</a></h2><p>Let's assume that $ e^x $ can be represented by weighted sum of the powers of x.</p>
<p>$ f(x) = e^x = a_0 \cdot x^0 + a_1 \cdot x^1 + a_2 \cdot x^2 + a_3 \cdot x^3 ... $</p>
<p>n'th derivative of the function is then:</p>
<p>$ f^{n}(x) = e^x = (n)(n-1)...(1) a_n \cdot x^0 + (n)(n-1)...(2) a_{n+1} \cdot x^1 ... $</p>
<p>Evaluating the n'th derivate at x=0 gives:</p>
<p>$ f^{n}(0) = 1 = (n)(n-1)...(1) a_n  $</p>
<p>Therefore,
$$a_n = \frac{1}{n!}$$</p>
<p>$$ e^x = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2!}x^2 + ... + \frac{1}{n!}x^n + ... $$</p>
<p>e can be evaluated from this equation by putting x=1</p>
<p>$$ e^1 = 1 + 1 + \frac{1}{2!} ... + \frac{1}{n!} + ... $$</p>
<p>The term diminishes as n goes larger toward infinity. This means that a few first terms provide good estimation of e and the accuacy can further be imporved by adding more terms.</p>
